, and the elimination of bishoprics, chapters, parishes and collegial churches — also adversely affected the wellbeing of these small urban communities not only in the Revolution but also in the two centuries that followed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aReligion and politicszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 70(DE-588)4018183-20(DE-627)1047679360(DE-576)208923136aFranzösische Revolution2gnd 70(DE-588)4031110-70(DE-627)1062672720(DE-576)208990607aKleinstadt2gnd 70(DE-588)4046514-70(DE-627)1041522060(DE-576)209069945aPolitik2gnd 70(DE-588)4049396-90(DE-627)1061871550(DE-576)209081880aReligion2gnd 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  a1791 Ecclesiastical Oath.  aFrench Revolution.  aGournay-en-Bray.  aHaguenau.  aIs-sur-Tille.  aPont-à-Mousson.  aVienne.  areligious institutions.  areligious politics.  asmall towns.  asocial capital.1 aWoell, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615914440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526159144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526159144/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles